Subject: [PATCH 0/5] fstests: five fixes from a btrfs UML/QEMU test campaign

These five patches fix test problems found while running the full btrfs
auto group repeatedly on User Mode Linux with QEMU/KVM cross-checking.
Each started as a suspected kernel bug and was root-caused to a test
issue with kernel-side instrumentation; the corresponding kernel was
exonerated in every case (details in each commit message).

- btrfs/081: bash >=5.2 wait diagnostics pollute the golden output.
- common/verity + generic/574: the generic corruption helper silently
  misses btrfs inline extents, producing a false "fs-verity does not
  detect corruption" failure; the helper now fails loudly and
  generic/574 forces real extents. Scoped per-test because btrfs/290
  corrupts inline extents on purpose (a global option broke it).
- btrfs/049: balance completes before "balance pause" lands on fast
  setups; retry with more block groups. Deterministic against current
  btrfs for-next.
- generic/747: btrfs statfs f_bavail counts unallocated space that DUP
  metadata growth then consumes, so the test's fill controller
  overshoots into genuine ENOSPC (pinned=0 at the failure instant);
  treat ENOSPC in the write phase as "actually full", which is the GC
  pressure the test wants anyway.

All five apply to current xfstests-dev HEAD and were validated on
btrfs (UML + QEMU/KVM, kernels 7.1-rc7, 7.2-rc1, btrfs for-next) and,
where relevant, ext4.

Mykola Lysenko (5):
  btrfs/081: suppress bash wait diagnostics for the reaped reader pid
  common/verity: fail loudly when corrupting a file without fiemap
    extents
  generic/574: force real extents on btrfs for sub-page corruption cases
  btrfs/049: retry when balance completes before it can be paused
  generic/747: tolerate ENOSPC from filesystems with approximate statfs

